{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17625408","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17625408"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:24:06+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:24:06+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17024"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17024","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17024"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.51,0.2,0.06,0.09,0.14]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9714"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68704"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9714","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9714"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17024"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54161"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"5059"},{"type":"tags","id":"10104"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22856"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22863"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68704","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/68704"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EDopamine receptors are important therapeutic targets in various neurological and psychiatric conditions. These receptors are also significant in endocrine disorders, particularly in the treatment of hyperprolactinaemia and growth hormone-secreting tumours. The receptors are classified into distinct families based on their molecular signalling mechanisms.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the effect of D1-like dopamine receptor activation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Stimulates adenylyl cyclase via Gs proteins","Stimulates guanyl cyclase via Gi proteins","Directly activates ion channels","Inhibits adenylyl cyclase via Gi proteins","Activates phospholipase C via Gq proteins"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Estimulation of adenylyl cyclase via Gs proteins\u003C/strong\u003E is the characteristic signalling mechanism of D1-like dopamine receptors (D1 and D5). This leads to increased cyclic adenosine monophosphate (cAMP) production and subsequent cellular responses.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStimulates guanyl cyclase via Gi proteins\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as D1-like receptors act through Gs proteins and adenylyl cyclase, not guanyl cyclase.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDirectly activates ion channels\u003C/strong\u003E is not the primary signalling mechanism of D1-like receptors, though downstream effects may influence ion channels.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInhibits adenylyl cyclase via Gi proteins\u003C/strong\u003E describes the mechanism of D2-like receptors (D2, D3, D4), which is distinct from D1-like receptor signalling.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EActivates phospholipase C via Gq proteins\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as D1-like receptors primarily signal through adenylyl cyclase pathways rather than phospholipase C signalling.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis classification of dopamine receptors based on their effects on adenylyl cyclase is important for understanding their physiological roles and developing targeted therapeutic approaches for conditions such as hyperprolactinaemia.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Dopamine receptors are classified into D1-like (D1, D5) and D2-like (D2, D3, D4) families based on their effects on adenylyl cyclase.","D1-like receptors stimulate adenylyl cyclase via Gs proteins, while D2-like receptors inhibit it via Gi proteins.","Understanding dopamine receptor classification is crucial for therapeutic targeting in conditions like Parkinson disease and schizophrenia."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54161"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17024"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54161","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/54161"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-10T11:38:36+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-10T11:41:30+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9714"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68704"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a 